You&#39;re using the wrong tool for the job. Java streams are the right tool for the job when the operations you need to do are either [A] an operation solely on a single element of a stream, or [B] an operation on all of them.

You want an operation on some of them (specifically, the &#39;predecessors&#39;). Stream, fundamentally, wasn&#39;t designed for that. You&#39;re using the wrong tool for the job. Stream has `.parallel()` for example, and in that view, the concept of &#39;the sum of all stuff before me&#39; doesn&#39;t even make sense anymore.

You can redefine the problem by involving the notion of sorting (&quot;I want the sum of all values from this key and everything that sorts before this key&quot;) but this would be ridiculously inefficient.

As is expectable when you attempt to use a tool for something it wasn&#39;t designed for, the stream version of this is either much slower, or an abomination (mixing stream and non-stream concepts, hence getting the downsides of both and the upsides of neither), and most likely much more code and much more complicated code.

Just use iterative processes - the operation as you&#39;ve defined is is much simpler with an iterative mindset. If you want to improve your code, remember: You should use the most specific type that accurately describes what you have. `Integer` doesn&#39;t say much, `LocalDate` is much more accurate, as the keys in your map are clearly dates, or at least, months+years.

```java
public class Hospital {
  SortedMap&lt;LocalDate, Long&gt; caseCounts = createCaseCountMap();
// createCaseCountMap ends up doing something like:
//    caseCounts.put(LocalDate.of(2021, 03, 1), 2);
//    caseCounts.put(LocalDate.of(2021, 04, 1), 4);
//    .... etc

// option 1:

  public long getSumUntil(LocalDate mark) {
    return caseCounts.headMap(mark, true).values().stream()
      .mapToLong(Long::longValue).sum();
  }

// option 2:

  public SortedMap&lt;LocalDate, Long&gt; makeIncrementalMap() {
    var out = new TreeMap&lt;LocalDate, Long&gt;();
    long sum = 0L;
    for (var entry : caseCounts.entrySet()) {
      sum += entry.getValue();
      out.put(entry.getKey(), sum);
    }
    return out;
  }
}
```

Here, for option 2, using streams is a very silly idea, given that the operation fundamentally depends on some but not all of its neighbours, which streams weren&#39;t meant for.

First, you need to *sort* the entries that you might make you of the `TreeMap`. 

And then want to solve this problem with streams at all costs to accumulate the *values* you might mimic the iteration over the *entry set* with for loop using the `iterate()` method.

The *first entry* of the sorted map is used as a **seed**. Then for every consecutive entry created in the stream, a key of the higher entry will be used as a key of a new entry and as value a sum of the value of the higher entry and a value of the previous entry from the stream. The process will continue until the higher entry exists, i.e. result returned by the `getAccumulatedEntry()` is not `null`. This condition is represented by the predicate `Objects::nonNull`.

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Map&lt;Integer, Long&gt; monthCaseCount =
                Map.of(202103, 2L,
                        202104, 4L,
                        202105, 0L,
                        202106, 9L);

        NavigableMap&lt;Integer, Long&gt; monthCaseCountSorted = new TreeMap&lt;&gt;(monthCaseCount);

        Map&lt;Integer, Long&gt; monthCaseCountAccumulated =
                Stream.iterate(monthCaseCountSorted.firstEntry(),
                               Objects::nonNull,
                               entry -&gt; getAccumulatedEntry(monthCaseCountSorted, entry))
                        .collect(Collectors.toMap(Map.Entry::getKey, Map.Entry::getValue));

        monthCaseCountAccumulated.entrySet().stream() // this part was added only for demonstration purpose
                .sorted(Map.Entry.comparingByKey())
                .forEach(entry -&gt; System.out.printf(&quot;%d : %d%n&quot;, entry.getKey(), entry.getValue()));
    }

    private static Map.Entry&lt;Integer, Long&gt; getAccumulatedEntry(NavigableMap&lt;Integer, Long&gt; monthCaseCountSorted,
                                                                Map.Entry&lt;Integer, Long&gt; entry) {
        Integer higher = monthCaseCountSorted.higherKey(entry.getKey());

        return higher == null ?
                null : Map.entry(higher, entry.getValue() + monthCaseCountSorted.get(higher));
    }

