Since this question is related to basic operations with collections I don&#39;t assume the knowledge of *lambda expressions* and *streams*. But for completeness and for *future readers*, I&#39;ll provide two other options that I&#39;ve mentioned above.

[*for information on lambda expressions and functional interfaces read this*](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/lambdaexpressions.html)

[to get familiar with Stream IPA take a look at this tutorial](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/ma14-java-se-8-streams.html)

The condition inside the method `filter()` in the stream pipeline and  [`Collection.removeIf()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Collection.html#removeIf(java.util.function.Predicate)) must defenetelly look familiar to you. Both method expect [`Predicate`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/function/Predicate.html) a function that takes an object and returns a boolean value. `Collection.removeIf()` will remove the element if the predicate returns `true`, but `filter()` does the opposite it&#39;ll retain the element if the predicate returns `true`.

So stream-based implementation might look like this:

    public static List&lt;Integer&gt; removeNumberIfStarsWith(List&lt;Integer&gt; source, int target) {
        return source.stream()
                .filter(item -&gt; !item.toString().startsWith(String.valueOf(target)))
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

Solution with `Collection.removeIf()`:

